  "event_preview": "The Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps is a 7.004 km (4.352 mi) permanent road course in the Ardennes forest in Stavelot, Belgium — the only track alongside Le Mans to have featured in every season of the FIA World Endurance Championship. The TotalEnergies 6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps is the second round of the 2026 season and the final competitive outing before the 24 Hours of Le Mans, with 17 Hypercars and 18 LMGT3 entries representing 14 manufacturers.\n\nToyota arrives on the back of victory at Imola, where the No. 8 TR010 Hybrid delivered the manufacturer its 50th WEC win on its 100th start. Ferrari, the reigning double world champion, locked out the top three Hyperpole positions and secured a 1-2 finish here in 2025, with Pier Guidi, Calado and Giovinazzi becoming the first Hypercar crew to win at Spa and claim the title in the same season. Louis Delétraz joins the No. 12 Cadillac in place of the recovering Alex Lynn, while Jack Aitken makes his full-time WEC debut in the sister No. 38. None of the four class winners at Spa in 2024 or 2025 started from the front row — a reminder that qualifying order counts for less here than almost anywhere else on the calendar.\n\nThe all-time Hypercar Hyperpole record belongs to Antonio Fuoco, who set a 1:59.617 in the No. 50 Ferrari 499P during the 2025 session — the first sub-two-minute Hypercar lap at this circuit. The LMGT3 Hyperpole record is Finn Gehrsitz's 2:17.732 in the No. 78 Akkodis ASP Lexus, also from 2025.",
